<abstract><para>The edges between neighboring habitats have long been recognized for their ecological

importance. The effects edges have on biota vary greatly with the physical 

structure and microclimate of the edge itself. The effects of edges may extend beyond the 

physical edge, altering the microclimate for some distance into the neighboring habitats. While 

there have been many studies on edge effects, most focus on how the abundance or behavior of 

individual species are affected; few focus on biodiversity in relation to edges, and even fewer 

involve invertebrates. Here I performed a correlative study observing the changes in the 

biodiversity of butterflies due to proximity to habitat edges and variations in microclimate 

conditions. Although results of this study indicate little support for a relationship between 

distance and diversity, this study indicated interactions between butterfly diversity and 

microclimate conditions. In this case, microclimate variables such as light and temperature 

related to butterfly diversity, however these relationships changed depending on the environment 

and habitat structure. This study provides insight into butterfly activity patterns and has 

important implications for future butterfly conservation strategies.</para>
</abstract>
